article.headline: Wright scores 23 and grabs nine rebounds
article.linkText: Wright time: Purdue avoids upset by Santa Barbara
article.story:
WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) -- Shereka Wright and the rest of the
Purdue Boilermakers didn't make many shots Friday night against UC
Santa Barbara.

But Wright made the one they needed -- a 3-pointer with 1:04 to
play to that propelled Purdue (No. 10 ESPN/USA Today, No. 8 AP) to a 65-61 win over UC Santa Barbara (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP).


"I was telling (teammate) Beth Jones that eventually I have to
hit one of these 3s," said Wright who led Purdue with 23 points
and nine rebounds, but was 0-for-4 from 3-point range up until
then. "That was the lift the team needed."

It certainly was.

The Gauchos (5-3) took a 58-57 lead with just over two minutes
to play on two free throws by Lindsay Taylor.

Wright responded with a jumper and then the 3-pointer on
consecutive possessions to give Purdue (8-1) a 62-58 lead.

"Either my team was going to die with me missing that shot or
win with me making it," Wright said. "I'm just happy I was able
to come through."

The shot helped Purdue overcome horrendous shooting in the first
half and being outrebounded 49-37.

Kristen Mann led UC Santa Barbara with 21 points and 10
rebounds. Taylor added 17 points and 14 rebounds.

"To be outrebounded and shoot as poorly as they did, it's a
credit to their team that they were still able to win," UC Santa
Barbara coach Mark French said. "That's what makes them so good --
they find ways to win."

The Boilermakers trailed the entire first half thanks to poor
shooting. Purdue shot 22 percent -- 7 of 32 -- in falling behind
30-25. Purdue still shot just 31 percent for the game after
shooting 32 percent against UCLA in a 58-57 win last week.

"Once again, we did not shoot the ball well," Wright said.
"We had to counter that with good defense. That can never let you
down."

The Boilermakers scored 14 points off 17 turnovers by the
Gauchos and only committed six turnovers themselves.

"Turnovers," UC Santa Barbara guard April McDivitt said with a
grimace. "That was the difference in the game."

Wright's timely shots helped overshadow strong performances by
Mann and the 6-foot-8 Taylor, who used an eight-inch height
advantage on counterpart Emily Heikes to dominate in the paint.

Taylor controlled the middle on both ends of the floor, blocking
shots and earning second-chance points with her rebounds.

That dominance, combined with Purdue's woeful shooting was
almost enough. But Purdue countered by making 21 of 28 free throws.
The Gauchos were 13 of 17 from the line.

Then, of course, there was Wright, who was dared to shoot the
outside shot all night by a collapsing Gaucho defense.

"That was our plan going in -- to make her hit that outside
shot," French said. "That's what great players do and she did
that."

The crowd erupted when the shot went through and a feeling of
relief swept over Wright.

"I was thinking, 'Yes, finally a shot goes in!" she said.
